pi/src/open/mod.rs:338): every spawn is `Command::new(binary)` with the directory passed via `.arg(&path)` or `.current_dir(&path)`. There is no `sh -c`, no string concatenation into a shell. That means a `path` like `\"; rm -rf ~\"` or `$(...)` is passed as a literal argument to the terminal binary, not interpreted — the classic shell-injection vector is structurally absent.\n\n**4. The executed binary is gated by an exhaustive `match` with a `bail!` default.** On every platform, an unrecognized `terminal_id` hits `_ => bail!(\"Unknown terminal: {terminal_id}\")` (e.g. mod.rs:456, :501, :569). So `arg0` can only ever be one of the known terminal binaries. You can't smuggle in an arbitrary executable.\n\n## The one thing worth being precise about (pre-existing, not introduced here)\n\nThe `open_in_terminal` / `open_url` / `show_in_finder` IPC commands accept frontend-controlled input and were already exposed before this PR — it only un-`legacy`'d them and re-registered the routes (but-server/src/lib.rs, gitbutler-tauri permissions/main.rs). So the threat model is unchanged. If a renderer were compromised (XSS in the webview), the worst it can do via these commands is **open a known terminal CWD'd to an attacker-chosen directory** or open a scheme-allowlisted URL — annoying, but not arbitrary command execution, precisely because of the no-shell pattern above.\n\nIf you want, I can also audit the `open_url` → `open_that` path (scheme allowlist at mod.rs:531) for SSRF/scheme-smuggling, since that's the other command being promoted out of `legacy` — but on the terminal/ACE question specifically, the PR is clean.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"parentUuid":"[REDACTED:entropy]","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","type":"message","role":"assistant","diagnostics":null,"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6327,"cache_rea